│   %sel = shl nuw i32 1, %2                                                             │
│ - The ctlz call retains the range(i32 1, 33) metadata.                                 │
│ - With x = -1: ctlz = 0; !range says it must be in [1,33), so using ctlz is poison.    │
│ The transformed code uses ctlz unconditionally via neg/and/shl, producing poison. The  │
│ source would have selected 1, avoiding poison.                                         │
│                                                                                        │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                │
│ foldBitCeil only considers arithmetic properties and the NUW dropping for the add      │
│ feeding the pattern, but it does not acknowledge poison-generating metadata on the     │
│ ctlz result. Range metadata is a semantic constraint that can make a value poison at   │
│ its use if it is outside the annotated bounds. By removing the select guard,           │
│ foldBitCeil must either prove the ctlz value cannot violate the annotated range or     │
│ prevent metadata from propagating poison unexpectedly. As it stands, it keeps the      │
│ range metadata on the ctlz result and then unconditionally uses it, which can increase │
│ poison propagation and thus breaks correctness.                                        │
│                                                                                        │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                             │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp                          │
│ - Location: in foldBitCeil, immediately after handling ShouldDropNUW, before building  │
│ the neg/and/shl sequence.                                                              │
│ - Edit: Clear the range metadata on the ctlz instruction to avoid increasing poison    │
│ due to metadata constraints when the guarding select is removed.                       │
