  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation in foldBitCeil removes a
guarding select and synthesizes a new shift count based on the ctlz result. In the source
IR, the ctlz call carries a range metadata !range [1, 33), which makes any actual value
that falls outside that range poison upon use. For %x = -1, ctlz(%x,false) = 0, which
violates the metadata range and becomes poison. In the original code, the poison-tainted
value only flows through the 'true' arm of the select, and the condition chooses the
'false' arm (constant 1), thus avoiding poison. The transformation eliminates the select
and unconditionally uses the ctlz-derived value, making the resulting program more
poisonous. Alive2 confirms this difference.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The first
transform point is foldBitCeil. It rewrites the select to:\n  %1 = sub nsw i32 0, %ctlz\n
%2 = and i32 %1, 31\n  %sel = shl nuw i32 1, %2\n- The ctlz call retains the range(i32 1,
33) metadata.\n- With x = -1: ctlz = 0; !range says it must be in [1,33), so using ctlz is
poison. The transformed code uses ctlz unconditionally via neg/and/shl, producing poison.
The source would have selected 1, avoiding poison.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nfoldBitCeil
only considers arithmetic properties and the NUW dropping for the add feeding the pattern,
but it does not acknowledge poison-generating metadata on the ctlz result. Range metadata
is a semantic constraint that can make a value poison at its use if it is outside the
annotated bounds. By removing the select guard, foldBitCeil must either prove the ctlz
value cannot violate the annotated range or prevent metadata from propagating poison
unexpectedly. As it stands, it keeps the range metadata on the ctlz result and then
unconditionally uses it, which can increase poison propagation and thus breaks
correctness.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:
llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp\n- Location: in foldBitCeil,
immediately after handling ShouldDropNUW, before building the neg/and/shl sequence.\n-
Edit: Clear the range metadata on the ctlz instruction to avoid increasing poison due to
metadata constraints when the guarding select is removed.\n\nProposed code change
(conceptual):\n\n  if (ShouldDropNUW)\n
cast<Instruction>(CtlzOp)->setHasNoUnsignedWrap(false);\n  \n  // The transformation
removes the guarding select and will use Ctlz\n  // unconditionally. If the ctlz call
carries range metadata that may be\n  // violated for some inputs (e.g. ctlz(0) == 0 with
is_zero_undef=false),\n  // keeping that metadata can turn the value poison at its use and
make the\n  // transformation more poisonous than the source. Clear the range metadata\n
// to preserve semantic equivalence.\n  if (auto *CtlzI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Ctlz))\n
CtlzI->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range, nullptr);\n\nThis is a minimal, safe fix that
ensures the derived use of ctlz is not constrained by potentially invalid range
annotations that were only safe under the original select guard.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe
bug stems from ignoring range metadata when removing the select guard in foldBitCeil.
Clearing the MD_range on the ctlz instruction before constructing the new shift sequence
prevents unintended poison propagation and restores correctness. This fix keeps the
optimization while ensuring it does not increase program poison compared to the original
IR.",
